title: ColourPalettes
type: text/vnd.tiddlywiki

A colour palette is a [[data tiddler|DataTiddlers]] that supplies a colour value for each of several colour names, like this:

```
page-background: #fe0
table-border: #ccc
tiddler-controls-foreground-selected: [tf.interpolate-colours[tiddler-background],[foreground],[0.9]]
```

<<.from-version "5.5.0">> Each entry is a filter expression that is evaluated to produce a [[CSS|Cascading Style Sheets]] colour value. An entry that is a plain CSS colour value, such as ''yellow'' or ''#fe0'', evaluates to itself. An entry can also compute its colour from other entries, using the [[Colour Operators]] and the function <<.var tf.colour>>, which retrieves another entry by name.

For backwards compatibility, entries of the classic form `<<colour name>>` are automatically converted to the equivalent filter `[tf.colour[name]]`. Other WikiText constructs are not supported, as palette entries are no longer wikified.

!! Functions for palette entries

Palette entries can use these core functions:

;<<.var tf.colour>>
: Returns the value of the palette entry named in its single parameter
;<<.var tf.interpolate-colours>>
: Blends the two palette entries named in its first two parameters, in the OKLCH colour space. The third parameter is the weight of the blend, from 0 (entirely the first entry) to 1 (entirely the second entry)
;<<.var tf.check-colour-contrast>>
: Used by [[readability tests|Palette Readability Tests]] to check the contrast between two entries

The system tiddler [[$:/palette]] always contains the title of the currently selected palette tiddler. You can switch palettes with the [[Palette Chooser]].

!! Palette compilation

When the wiki starts, and whenever the current palette changes, the palette is <<.def compiled>>: each entry is evaluated, and the resulting plain CSS colour values are stored in the temporary tiddler <<.tid "$:/temp/palette-colours">>. The <<.mlink colour>> function reads from the compiled palette, so that colours can be used without evaluating the palette entries again.

Compilation is triggered automatically by a [[background action|Background Actions]] that tracks the palette, so custom code that changes [[$:/palette]] does not need to take any special steps.

!! Palette tiddler fields

Palette tiddlers have the following fields:

|!Name |!Value |
|title |Typically starting with `$:/palettes/` |
|type |`application/x-tiddler-dictionary` |
|tags |`$:/tags/Palette` |
|name |Displayed in the palette chooser |
|description |Displayed in the palette chooser |
|color-scheme |<<.from-version "5.5.0">> Optional filter determining the active [[colour scheme|Colour Schemes]] |
|palette-import |<<.from-version "5.5.0">> Optional title of another palette to import; see [[Palette Inheritance]] |
|customisations |<<.from-version "5.5.0">> Optional title of a customisations panel shown beneath the chooser; see [[Palette Customisations]] |
|category |<<.from-version "5.5.0">> Optional descriptive category |
|text |`name: value` colour definitions |

Entries whose names begin with `?` are [[readability tests|Palette Readability Tests]] rather than colours.

!! Palette customisations

<<.from-version "5.5.0">> The <<.field customisations>> field gives the title of a tiddler that is transcluded beneath the [[Palette Chooser]] whenever the palette is selected. It typically contains controls that write to the customisation layer described below, and the palette is automatically recompiled as they change.

For example, this customisations tiddler offers a colour picker for the `base-paper` entry:

```
title: $:/palettes/MyPalette/Customisations

Paper: <$edit-text tiddler={{{ [function[tf.palette-customisations-layer]] }}} index="base-paper" type="color" tag="input" default={{{ [function[colour],[base-paper]] }}} inputActions="<$action-setfield $tiddler={{{ [function[tf.palette-customisations-layer]] }}} palette-import={{$:/palette}}/>"/>
```

The <<.attr inputActions>> attribute sets the <<.field palette-import>> field on the layer, which is required before the layer is used in compilation.

The core palette ~TwentyTwenties uses this technique to offer a colour picker for each of its base colours, and ~AutoToggle to offer dropdowns choosing the palettes to use in light and dark modes. Because fields are [[inherited|Palette Inheritance]], a palette that imports another palette also inherits its customisations panel unless it overrides the <<.field customisations>> field.

Customisations are stored in a layer tiddler titled <<.tid "$:/config/PaletteCustomisations/">> followed by the palette title. The layer imports the palette itself, and is compiled in its place while it exists, so the palette tiddler is not modified. Deleting the layer removes the customisations.

!! Under the covers

The compilation process is implemented in [[$:/core/macros/CSS]]. It generates two temporary tiddlers:

|!Title |!Content |
|<<.tid "$:/temp/palette-consolidated">> |The result of merging the current palette with its chain of [[imported palettes|Palette Inheritance]]. The entries are the raw filter expressions, not the computed colours |
|<<.tid "$:/temp/palette-colours">> |The computed CSS colour value of each entry |

The [[background action|Background Actions]] <<.tid "$:/core/background-actions/AutoCompilePalette">> triggers recompilation when [[$:/palette]] changes, when the [[colour scheme|Colour Schemes]] of the current palette changes, or when any palette, background palette or customisation layer changes.

If [[$:/palette]] names a tiddler that does not exist, the default Vanilla palette is compiled in its place.

